Debate basically boils down to this moral question:<br>
<br>
Is the potential for a human morally the same as an actual human?<br>
<br>
<br>
Assuming some other moral authority (like a god, your parents, the voices in your head, etc.) is not telling you what to believe:<br>
<br>
If yes, then aborting a fetus is morally equal to killing your neighbor. (Pro-life stance.)<br>
<br>
If no, then aborting a fetus is morally equal to having a wart removed. (Pro-choice stance)<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, its not morally clear cut whether potential = actual, and thus we have this wonderful dead horse argument.<br>
<br>
I hope I didn't slant it either way. I merely meant to outline why this debate never dies. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub27.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vainne>Vainne</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Night-blind Bard</span><br>  Posts: 2276<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(1/24/03 2:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3077.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Surprisingly simple</span><hr size=1> Well its the word pontificate I'd stress there. Or something.<br>
